snippet.textDisplay:
If it works, it's obsolete. It’s only when a thing has become obsolete that everybody is sufficiently familiar with it to make it work.

"Our motorcars were obsolete long ago, but that means they are really going concerns. There is more writing today than there was before Gutenberg — more handwriting. Obsolescence does not mean the conclusion, but rather the beginning, of a process as far as everyday life is concerned. This is not ordinarily understood. Most people think obsolescence means the end. It means the beginning. People always live with obsolescent attitudes and obsolescent frames of mind and obsolescent technologies and homes. Obsolescence is the moment of superabundance."

64gb storage, 4gb RAM, 5.8" screen, 12MP rear 8MP front cameras, 3000mAh battery, rear fingerprint scanner. 128gb storage on the latest & fastest 3.0 chip, 12gb RAM, 6.9" screen with 120hz, 108MP primary 12MP ultra-wide 48MP telephoto with 10x optical & 100x digital zoom rear cameras with a 48MP front wide angle lens, 5000mAh battery, in screen fingerprint scanner.

And even in design there's been improvements. In the 3 years, the bezels are basically non-existent which means no more curved "infinity" displays that resulted in many accidental touches. No more AUX jack which means more battery & better haptic feedback.

Then we're also about to get another smartphone advancement. Graphene Batteries. I know they're talking about being able to make thinner phones with this tech. But personally, I would like to see them make Li-ion sized graphene batteries with like 50000mAh capacity to power some 8k 120hz screen.

snippet.textDisplay:
In my opinion things plateaued (or even went back in quality) when they didn't need to:
-Battery life my first phone lasted 3-4 days this shouldn't have went backwards or taken this long to get there again
-Screen pixel density (apple iphone 11?)
-Form factor (yeah flip is new? but the glass sandwich trend isn't innovative) as you stated
-worse quality front facing cameras than the rear when most people probably take selfies?
-software upgrades forcing the upgrades (first phone still works from 2007 and I used it for 3 years no software upgrade)
-can't take out batteries (it was nice to have a backup battery to swap out)
-phones storage in many cases don't allow for expandable storage and limiting phones to 16gb-512gb (I lol at even 64gb because these phones can now record 4k 60fps and storage options doesn't compensate or scale to keep up for this) also this storage is cheap (but companies charge +200$ dollars for that small storage upgrade when a microssd is 30$ for 200gbs)
-Also prices have inflated significantly, 250$ is expensive, a quality phone should cost this I can't believe we are brainwashed in 500+$ is budget
-headphone jack still matters (nobody wants to spend time worrying about charging another thing and eventually replacing when the battery gives)
-these phones are delicate, nokia strength should have been standard
-don't even get me started about not being able to fix the phones yourself and cost and system of repairing phones


It's also worth saying that phones were used as communication devices. I can say my pixel doesn't sound crystal clear during a phone call and there's still areas that I get poor coverage. I know this is a carrier problem but still should be addressed before I can say we are peak smartphone. A phones identify is now much of a tech multi-tool which I can't say has peaked.


I think smartphones have peaked to cost the customer the most amount of money.


Unfortunately I feel companies prioritise user experience for a set window of time (1-1.5 years) and how much money they can make rather than making a long term reliable and affordable phone.


Cars are not at peak design. Cars were made to replace horses but the fundamental problem is safe and fast long distance travel. Cars still are not safe and traffic (self driving this should help) but fundamentally it should be safer than trains/planes and optimised to never sit in a parking lot. Also cost to use should be affordable for the the median income person.

snippet.textDisplay:
Yes (for the average consumer), but no (for the tech head). People are hanging onto their phones longer as improvements become incremental while prices climb. Much like TV tried to reinvigorate their market after the initial digital boom with 3DTV and curved displays, the phone manufacturers are throwing everything at consumers to recapture their interest; gaming phones, modular designs, dual displays and foldables (which personally I think takes a phone and a tablet, and gives you the worst of both). But when the core usage for most people is talk, text, snap, browse and watch, most phones now are perfectly fine. Sure some are incrementally better at certain features, but we're not seeing the benefits we used to, especially with the prices they're asking. There isn't a $750 better experience to be found in an iPhone 11 Pro Max over a Pixel 3A, but then some people can buy a BMW M3, while most others will buy a Mazda 3.

Tech heads and phone geeks will always be interested in the latest innovations and the unique ideas out on the periphery, its why channels like this exist and have an audience, but for consumers phones have now entered the same space of most other goods; Buy, Use, Die, Replace.
